{{Infobox film | name = Moseka | image = | caption = | director = [[Roger Kwami Mambu Zinga]] | producer = Institut des Arts de Diffusion | writer = | starring = | distributor = | released = 1971 | runtime = 24 minutes | country = Democratic Republic of the Congo | language = | budget = | gross = | screenplay = Félix Blaise Malutuma | cinematography = Sandro Usai | editing = Robert Couez | music = }}
'''''Moseka''''' is a 1971 documentary film.
== Synopsis == Moseka, a young woman from [[Zaire]], travels to Europe to study. With her braided hair and traditional clothes, she is the laughingstock of her fellow students who strive to look European, adopting wigs and European clothing. The film tells of the depersonalization of young Africans when they enter into contact with the European culture. In this sense, the film fits into the "[[Authenticité (Zaire)|authenticity policy]]" of [[Mobutu]].<ref name=" Ndombasi">{{cite book | title=Le cinéma du congo Démocratique | author=Ndombasi, Gansa | year=2008 | isbn=978-2-296-06204-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ts1ZNqKWqGMC&pg=PA40&dq=Moseka+film&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-jBeT_3NO-jm0QHmt5SECg&ved=0CDIQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=Moseka%20film&f=false | chapter=Les films zairois|pages=37–40|language=French|accessdate=12 March 2012}}</ref>
==Awards== ''Moseka'' was named best short film at the [[List of FESPACO award winners#3rd FESPACO (1972)|3rd Panafrican Film and Television Festival of Ouagadougou]] (FESPACO).<ref name=Diawara>{{cite book|last=Diawara|first=Manthia|title=African Cinema|year=1992|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|isbn=978-0-253-20707-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lIjrlnC0bmsC&pg=PA131&dq=Moseka+film&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Pi1eT4KfHNS20QGv19nDDw&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Moseka%20film&f=false|accessdate=12 March 2012|page=131}}</ref>
